    <fr:title text="Equivalence relation">Equivalence relation</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <html:p>A relation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E\colon  A\mathbin {\nrightarrow } A]]></fr:tex> is called an <html:em><html:strong>equivalence relation</html:strong></html:em> when it is <fr:link href="/jms-00JX/" title="Preorder" uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00JX/" display-uri="jms-00JX" type="local">reflexive, transitive</fr:link>, and symmetric:</html:p>
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \forall  x\in  A\mathpunct {.} x\mathrel {E}x
]]></fr:tex>
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \forall  x,y,z\in  A\mathpunct {.} x\mathrel {E} y \land  y \mathrel {E} z \implies  x \mathrel {E} z
]]></fr:tex>
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \forall  x,y\in  A\mathpunct {.} x \mathrel {E} y \implies  y\mathrel {E}x
]]></fr:tex>
    <html:p>We will write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {EqRel}{\mathopen {}\left (A\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> for the set of all equivalence relations on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
