            <fr:title text="Equivalence class">Equivalence class</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E\colon  A\mathbin {\nrightarrow } A]]></fr:tex> be an <fr:link href="/jms-00L4/" title="Equivalence relation" uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00L4/" display-uri="jms-00L4" type="local">equivalence relation</fr:link> on a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>. The <html:em><html:strong>equivalence class</html:strong></html:em> of a given element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> is the subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [a\right  ]\mathclose {}}_{E}\subseteq  A]]></fr:tex> spanned by elements related to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex>, i.e. <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [a\right  ]\mathclose {}}_{E} = {\mathopen {}\left \{x\in  A\,\middle \vert \,x\mathrel {E}a\right \}\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
